8HWJO8h47xnP-w7j0t0V6zvstYLycRzQVulf6Qd28AhVcSf4yP5jiKJn8IsSj_HIaqcC_4HZmzjMptzn1PlHRKBvrXGKF2pEiEKdoEKJMYUGxb-mBxB5VbkJxQBYyd8S6lpNVMdQ4zdizl7axeeg8m3dJYoDimPhWZkbPfgxwq45lYvIdnlVdZlhUWWznXtRzD67_A1ciQ179WWONvC2Z2ukLwRIizyyyFHX5fDTHqE4wRWFnjSdlO\\\",\\\"summary\\\":[{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Considering Scala package structure**\\\\n\\\\nI see that I'm reflecting on the structure of code packages in Scala. It’s quite clear that placing tests in the same package as a library just to access package-private or internal code isn’t ideal. I might consider using Scala 3's \\\\\\\"exported private given\\\\\\\" feature, which could help manage access more cleanly. It seems like there’s a lot of thought that needs to go into organizing code efficiently!\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring dynamic access coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm thinking about how dynamic access coverage might be generated from jacoco during test runtime, not at compile time. It seems like our macro execution during `compileTestScala` won’t contribute to coverage after all. Ah, key insight! Active class dynamic access call sites only exist at compile time. So, the native-agent dynamic access report likely comes from the JVM at test runtime. That makes invoking the macro at runtime necessary, but I need to be cautious about runtime compilation and class loading.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Deciding on test execution**\\\\n\\\\nI’m trying to evaluate whether I should add or refine tests as the user requested. The user's guidance says to use Scala 3 tests that exercise macros. It seems running the compiler at test runtime could be acceptable. But the developer explicitly mentioned not to create tests relying on runtime bytecode generation or custom class loaders. I wonder if invoking the compiler for typechecking is still allowed, especially since native images must also pass tests.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring native image challenges**\\\\n\\\\nI'm wondering if the Scala 3 compiler dependency in a native image can handle parsing and type checking without class generation. It might rely on reflection and classloaders. Existing tests seem to invoke the compiler only during the macro compilation phase. At runtime, the native test won’t have the compiler available, which could complicate things. A possible solution might be to separate JUnit tests to assert precomputed values, but that could limit coverage. I should check the output XML for dynamic report details.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_prkxaTLR793U6IFWt3oQG9Cp|fc_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a7b24a8819789535e2c4927a1b4\", \"name\": \"read\", \"arguments\": {\"path\": \"tests/src/com.beachape/enumeratum-macros_3/1.9.0/build/test-results/test/TEST-com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest.xml\", \"limit\": 120}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"oca/gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 8928, \"output\": 2290, \"cacheRead\": 49664, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 60882, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1782475332287, \"responseId\": \"resp_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a45a5dc81979abaca74ab26e4b6\"}}\n[tool-exec] start id=call_prkxaTLR793U6IFWt3oQG9Cp|fc_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a7b24a8819789535e2c4927a1b4 name=read args={\"path\": \"tests/src/com.beachape/enumeratum-macros_3/1.9.0/build/test-results/test/TEST-com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest.xml\", \"limit\": 120}\n[tool-exec] end id=call_prkxaTLR793U6IFWt3oQG9Cp|fc_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a7b24a8819789535e2c4927a1b4 name=read status=success\n  <?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n  <testsuite name=\"com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest\" tests=\"1\" skipped=\"0\" failures=\"0\" errors=\"0\" timestamp=\"2026-06-26T11:56:49.691Z\" hostname=\"kung-fu-workstation\" time=\"0.103\">\n    <properties/>\n    <testcase name=\"stringValueEntriesAreDiscoveredFromSingletonEntries()\" classname=\"com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest\" time=\"0.103\"/>\n    <system-out><![CDATA[]]></system-out>\n    <system-err><![CDATA[]]></system-err>\n  </testsuite>\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_start\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_prkxaTLR793U6IFWt3oQG9Cp|fc_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a7b24a8819789535e2c4927a1b4\", \"toolName\": \"read\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"<?xml version=\\\"1.0\\\" encoding=\\\"UTF-8\\\"?>\\n<testsuite name=\\\"com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest\\\" tests=\\\"1\\\" skipped=\\\"0\\\" failures=\\\"0\\\" errors=\\\"0\\\" timestamp=\\\"2026-06-26T11:56:49.691Z\\\" hostname=\\\"kung-fu-workstation\\\" time=\\\"0.103\\\">\\n  <properties/>\\n  <testcase name=\\\"stringValueEntriesAreDiscoveredFromSingletonEntries()\\\" classname=\\\"com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest\\\" time=\\\"0.103\\\"/>\\n  <system-out><![CDATA[]]></system-out>\\n  <system-err><![CDATA[]]></system-err>\\n</testsuite>\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1782475387545}}\n[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"toolResult\", \"toolCallId\": \"call_prkxaTLR793U6IFWt3oQG9Cp|fc_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a7b24a8819789535e2c4927a1b4\", \"toolName\": \"read\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"text\", \"text\": \"<?xml version=\\\"1.0\\\" encoding=\\\"UTF-8\\\"?>\\n<testsuite name=\\\"com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest\\\" tests=\\\"1\\\" skipped=\\\"0\\\" failures=\\\"0\\\" errors=\\\"0\\\" timestamp=\\\"2026-06-26T11:56:49.691Z\\\" hostname=\\\"kung-fu-workstation\\\" time=\\\"0.103\\\">\\n  <properties/>\\n  <testcase name=\\\"stringValueEntriesAreDiscoveredFromSingletonEntries()\\\" classname=\\\"com_beachape.enumeratum_macros_3.ValueEnumMacrosInnerValueOfFromExprTest\\\" time=\\\"0.103\\\"/>\\n  <system-out><![CDATA[]]></system-out>\\n  <system-err><![CDATA[]]></system-err>\\n</testsuite>\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1782475387545}}\n[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering Scala package structure**\\n\\nI see that I'm reflecting on the structure of code packages in Scala. It’s quite clear that placing tests in the same package as a library just to access package-private or internal code isn’t ideal. I might consider using Scala 3's \\\"exported private given\\\" feature, which could help manage access more cleanly. It seems like there’s a lot of thought that needs to go into organizing code efficiently!\\n\\n**Exploring dynamic access coverage**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how dynamic access coverage might be generated from jacoco during test runtime, not at compile time. It seems like our macro execution during `compileTestScala` won’t contribute to coverage after all. Ah, key insight! Active class dynamic access call sites only exist at compile time. So, the native-agent dynamic access report likely comes from the JVM at test runtime. That makes invoking the macro at runtime necessary, but I need to be cautious about runtime compilation and class loading.\\n\\n**Deciding on test execution**\\n\\nI’m trying to evaluate whether I should add or refine tests as the user requested. The user's guidance says to use Scala 3 tests that exercise macros. It seems running the compiler at test runtime could be acceptable. But the developer explicitly mentioned not to create tests relying on runtime bytecode generation or custom class loaders. I wonder if invoking the compiler for typechecking is still allowed, especially since native images must also pass tests.\\n\\n**Exploring native image challenges**\\n\\nI'm wondering if the Scala 3 compiler dependency in a native image can handle parsing and type checking without class generation. It might rely on reflection and classloaders. Existing tests seem to invoke the compiler only during the macro compilation phase. At runtime, the native test won’t have the compiler available, which could complicate things. A possible solution might be to separate JUnit tests to assert precomputed values, but that could limit coverage. I should check the output XML for dynamic report details.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0034f1349302b464016a3e6a46c21c819798046b4742d1e64e\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"content\\\":[],\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqPmp7pLkD1JVLz2id7C1gIklWO9DFA2rmw633bH1WF1TV0iCZu37pho5y59ryOjSasYOLgBXxW4TjFu3VWRtO69V7hde0TfCkhHs8SEQXTQWDSfmiDQO2rad62jefG2CvOIrUZ2gnW4rINu4ITOdkYdpTVfHjmTenso2yp2yKJXShcCt1AnrMreICOHbNWzKvU3TlQXF63C6Zqq0k2GoFrPE_-OtZVBs27kxq2xqxHb6IGr3dEuYmmx20uZXDKt-F6zJHYNlPsvlE8d5HTDLePw8M3gKZPLhVehruRMNkyD27qIfqSIEnE-zEXgE3I0DDWM3xBIXSGjk21d1FQHSo7_TZ0pZJuTdxPyoc0EqJijIElWn6MeE1Tv58k3rcV6e4egAdnUp-KRrKhVI3uiRlkH5RZKx4pwFyHOPskDczTb85RHfjDbFOS3hv5B98H74svF6GjibXw58JR9BfP4TH7wxrRvj8jwXn_iE2_Inn1o8TVrTBOcMHNe5JT6JHzenq79teSSEq0to2Zy2xcvtsVYqWyuxtuFscLoLMtUS1zyrryxMA7uQ74l532yCkwH2VNv_pPYWLmwUDiZV6YIHy_8zwZdVnpo-WVM4u1hf7nyTaZp-ZjrkdQyBP8DC-UNZSUgSESikAJyeQcYfRQeOn3WmEZH0APg_OFarwVJSkdeiADPeSCfECnBFyFITfJGmoJm07CRnINg5oDUt1jPY4PHSWQFX85OTAGf4mUJkHUnU7qZ_hO9FTl_rK_2dvVQUr0cSgZKUXA4yLEeMVmc6XTEXMTXBNWrjK8-Bh2AUskDvvrJyzXkoVP4CDHp1ACvzMbknu1RSq06psCKO7rzstc5DEcqoj6fxZ7Ft6tybh115_VFHJGclCak4WI4W_Gitbq4hYuyzeV9W8lzrVipWKxWv4RR_knCHXQqL6XvSwDLKY__hnIyDWwGVjmBXSgAnjq4YkT8gA8UwZHVS1kjtp12E4ZMVs5hZLfh7XlhYiL9hQcyz4MiRh6O2rso52ZbgXFbdmNWqMtGoX2LCsXY-cZJpO4JM01LKViBqubHaGN7BlNhDL7Wi1Fz8gurtMKLnVc5UptkfqSGNwj4lNsw-TFlZKKh0t9rJ8uAogkrAFO7iP5BbhTPrCdesFbY33nfIzYx1hM0cZIl0JVlnSgUSyWxwjzhtx5eMPTGsD5nSThPfp1NkVjYljShIPDzGpop7nw10BvCH2kHax11-RaIoSrVEEsZ5lfqy2wlULjXFwFQX2cXLq-zQUQUMNrBfVOgRbh9_PtCFXSFsEl4gGhn5jrVfK8vyp8